**Course Number and Name:** CST 204 081 \- *Database Management Systems*  
**Term Dates:** 01/21/2025 \- 05/14/2025  
**Meeting Location:** Kellogg Building K-218  
**Meeting Days & Times:** Th; 2:00PM \- 4:40PM  
**Lecture/Lab Hours:** 3.00 Lecture Hours  
**Credits:** 3.00  
**Prerequisite(s):** CST-101 OR CST-130 OR CST-161  
**Course Description:** This course focuses on the principles, design, implementation, and maintenance of database management systems, with an emphasis on practical, hands-on experience. Students will explore key topics such as data modeling, normalization, database security, privacy, and performance optimization. Through real-world applications, they will learn to design, validate, and manage relational databases using industry-standard tools. The course also includes comprehensive instruction in Structured Query Language (SQL), equipping students to query, manipulate, and manage data effectively within relational database management systems. Additional topics include creating user forms, generating reports, and integrating databases with web applications to prepare students for modern data-driven environments.

## Course Learning Outcomes

**Upon successful completion of this course, students will be able to:**

1. Explain the importance of data models and how they are used, relational database operators, the data dictionary, and the system catalog  
2. Summarize normalization and what role it plays in the database design process  
3. List the characteristics of good primary keys and how to select them  
4. Use the basic commands and functions of SQL  
5. Design, implement, test, and evaluate databases as part of information systems  
6. Describe database administration and the skills required by a DBA including communication and ethical skills.   
7. Locate, discern, and effectively use information to solve issues and/or problems.

## Course Schedule

| Week | Topic | Details |
| :---- | :---- | :---- |
| Week 1 | Introduction to Databases, Tools, and Environment Setup | Overview of databases and relational concepts. Installing and setting up MySQL Workbench and server. |
| Week 2 | Introduction to SQL | SELECT statements, creating views, and understanding tables. Hands-on: Writing basic SQL queries. |
| Week 3 | Database Design and ER Models | Basics of ER modeling and diagramming. Hands-on: Creating ER diagrams and translating them into SQL. |
| Week 4 | Data Manipulation Language (DML) in SQL | INSERT, UPDATE, DELETE, and data constraints. Hands-on: Practicing DML on sample databases. |
| Week 5 | Advanced SQL Queries | Joins, GROUP BY, and aggregations. Hands-on: Writing advanced queries. |
| Week 6 | Normalization and Relational Models | Functional dependencies and normalization (1NF, 2NF, 3NF). Hands-on: Normalizing denormalized datasets. |
| Week 7 | SQL Subqueries and Views | Writing subqueries, nested queries, and creating views. Hands-on: Simplifying queries using views. |
| Week 8 | Web Integration with MySQL | Connecting databases to web applications with Python and HTML. Hands-on: Building a basic database-backed web application. |
| Week 9 | Collaborative Team Project Kickoff | Students begin team projects to develop a database-backed web application. |
| Week 10 | Transactions and Database Integrity | Transaction processing, ACID properties, commits, and rollbacks. Hands-on: Creating transaction scripts in SQL. |
| Week 11 | Stored Procedures and Functions | Writing and using stored routines and triggers. Hands-on: Developing stored procedures to enforce data integrity. |
| Week 12 | Performance Optimization and Indexing | Creating and evaluating indexes for query performance. Hands-on: Analyzing query performance with and without indexes. |
| Week 13 | Final Project Development | Teams finalize and debug their projects. |
| Week 14 | Presentations and Database Administration Basics | Teams present their projects. Introduction to database administration and security. |
| Week 15 | Final Exam and Course Wrap-Up | Review and final assessment. |
